“When it comes to reality it was really different. At that time I scared that marriage is not only about the sum of being husband and wife to society. Another part is physical and emotional attachment as well. So I think to quit that relationship.” Anuj Peter, a 30 year old #gay man from #Nepal, is an activist at the LGBTQI＋ organization in #Kathmandu, #BlueDiamondSociety.  It took him a long time to understand his sexual orientation and to accept himself. Facing the pressures in Nepalese society to marry, Anuj decided to get engaged to a woman, but soon realized “this is not my right to make her life destroy”. After meeting members of the Blue Diamond Society at an unofficial gay club, Anuj started to come out of his shell. He told his story and came out on national television in 2015 and soon decided to work with his community. “My parents were ok with it but they request not to be come were like this in media, we accept what you are but this stay with the family only. Then I start thing of doing my community. And which I thing many gay guys are still hide his sexuality and their relationship. So I start work about marriage equality. Now I work on the issues to the country.”
//
