“They hurt my spirit but they have not broken me. My sexuality has prevented me from getting work, and I have often wondered why people are so mean to me.” Nillam Poudel is a 27 year old activist, model, make-up artist and #transgenderwoman from #Nepal. Growing up, Nillam would always wear women’s clothes, but after being scolded by her father, she would change. Nowadays, she has been accepted by her family, but she lives with a burden to provide for them as best as she can. Nillam moved to Kathmandu in search for work and higher paying jobs, but has been consistently discriminated against by the Nepalese society. “The best thing has been acceptance from family , friends and being able to accept my own identity. The worst aspect has been lack of respect from society. People still use derogative term. I don’t feel bad , I feel bad for their children. If parents are like that, what kind of education will the children get?” Nillam writes, “I woud be lying if I said I am not experiencing depression...I have seen my friends hurt themselves because their families have not accepted them. Many have become alcoholics, while many others have committed suicide.” Although Nillam has deeply struggled from the discrimination she experiences, she has bravely set her goals: “In the future, I want to start a place for LGBTI folks, like an old age home, for people who have been thrown away from their families or home, or those who are old and cannot work.“ She concludes her story by writing: “Those of you who will see this… In 21st century, there is bound to be somebody who is from LGBT community near your community, but they might not be open because of you. When you accept LGBTI people who are already out, it will better your family. Accept everyone.”
//
