“They all thought I was moving to pursue higher education, But there’s something else, which, only I knew.” In 2014, Pradeep, a #gay man from #India, received his visa to go to Canada. Two years later he came out to his family, and because of their reactions, he hasn’t hugged his mother in almost three years and has yet to go back home to India. “I WAS ASKED SO MANY TIMES TO SAY YES TO GO TO A DOCTOR, WHO(THEY ALL THINK) COULD MAKE ME A STRAIGHT MAN. I WAS SUGGESTED TO KEEP PRAYING TO GOD(I COME FROM A CATHOLIC BACKGROUND).” For years, Pradeep has tried to explain to his family that his being gay is not a choice, that he is normal and that sexual orientation is not something that can be changed. Pradeep misses his family, but he is tired of explaining himself. “I THINK I DID MY BEST AND CAN’T SPEND ANYMORE TIME ON IT.  I nEVER ASKed my cousins and friends WHY They LIKED/LOVED WHO They LOVED. Never tried suggesting them about who they should HAVE SEX WITH OR SHARE their LIFE WITH. They were never ASKED and FORCED TO EXPLAIN WHO They ARE, NOT ONCE OR TWICE BUT MANY TIMES by many people. I always wondered why they don’t realize that. they asked me questions and tried to force their ideas upon me many times and I bet they would never like to be treated that way.”
//
